I will install the second completed nest box over the weekend, and then release more information.
In 2015, birds' internet speeds were faster than mine.
At least that's the plan for now.
There is already one nest box connected to the home's wireless network.
The other one will need some work to get online.
I hung up the new nest box during the day. This is how it looks in the garden.
But let's take a step back for a moment. "What's inside?" doesn't seem to be a question anyone asks.
At the top is an ESP32 camera board with a fisheye lens camera, and an infrared LED light that I took from a Raspberry Pi camera.
The plastic box has an unusual shape because the side panels of the nest box can rotate. When I bought it, it was like that and couldn't be modified, so I had to design around it.
Since there's no power source in the garden, the entire setup runs on a solar panel and a 2600mAh 18650 lithium-ion battery.
I didn't take photos of the battery or charger, but here's a photo of the solar panel.
The battery is housed in a gray box attached to the side of the nest box.
It can run for about 4 hours after charging.
I call this a "special feature." This way, the birds have a bit of privacy too.
At first, I wasn't sure if the network in the garden would be strong enough to support this setup. The old access points I replaced last autumn definitely wouldn't cut it.
But the new access point has perfect coverage.
Now I don't even need to install a TP-Link CPE210 on the roof pointing down at the garden.
If I were to build more nest boxes with cameras in the future, I might still do it this way. Especially in places farther from the house, I might need it.
Now, the camera has gone offline for reasons I don't yet understand. It stopped working just an hour after sunset.
Maybe it's because of insufficient lighting; it might have stopped charging three hours before sunset.
Maybe half a day isn't enough time for it to fully charge.
Let's see what happens tomorrow.
I don't have telemetry data with the battery. Future versions might include this feature.
I think it would be better with more sensors.
