And it's also offline.
Great.
Based on the orientation of the solar panels installed on the house, the actual time they receive sunlight is only about 90 minutes.
Wait another hour or two to see if it does anything (or nothing).
Still offline.
Sigh, nothing worth doing is easy.
It turns out that the USB-C splitter board I used to connect the battery charger had the 5V line and GND line printed in reverse.
After swapping the wires around, the charging indicator light came on.
ESP didn't come online right away; let's wait a few more minutes.
An hour passed, and it was still offline.
It seems it got stuck in a reboot loop, triggering Tasmota's reset function.
This board seems really junky. I've ordered a larger one, hoping it will solve the problem.
Let's see what I found in my workshop.
This is a 24-volt solar panel. Unfortunately, the sun is too low (and there's a tree blocking it), and as soon as I added a load, the voltage dropped significantly.
It looks like I won't know whether this solar panel is sufficient or if I need the better-performing one I ordered until tomorrow.
The information on Amazon states that this solar panel was purchased in 2021 with a maximum output of 12V at 1.2A.
So either this solar panel is defective, or my multimeter is faulty, or they have changed the product page.
Hello everyone, good news!
They changed the product page; the one I have is defective.
The title on both the old and new product pages calls it a 12V 10W solar panel.
This is why I didn't delete the old email.
Hey, look: it reconnected about an hour ago, but only for less than half a minute.
Maybe the solar panel charged the battery just enough to run for 38 seconds. That's all the time we've got in two hours.
Guess what: it's cloudy today! So I'm not sure if that (possibly broken) solar panel can generate enough power to work.
Let's see.
Latest update: the new solar panel is installed and seems to be working properly now.
Maybe it will stop working as soon as the sun sets, but let's see.
Interestingly, I am using Home Assistant's ping integration to monitor whether it is online.
